const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: [
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What are adaptogens?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Adaptogens are a class of herbs and mushrooms that help the body resist and adapt to physical, chemical, and biological stressors. The term was coined by Soviet scientist N.V. Lazarev in 1947 and formalized by Israel Brekhman, who established three criteria: adaptogens must be non-toxic at normal doses, they must help the body resist a broad range of stressors, and they must have a normalizing effect — meaning they help bring overactive systems down and underactive systems up. Clinically studied adaptogens include ashwagandha (KSM-66, Sensoril), rhodiola rosea, holy basil (tulsi), eleuthero (Siberian ginseng), schisandra, and reishi mushroom. Each works through different mechanisms but shares the common property of modulating the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis — the body\'s central stress response system.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How do adaptogens reduce stress?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Adaptogens modulate the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, which governs the body\'s cortisol response to stress. When you encounter a stressor, the HPA axis triggers cortisol release. Chronic stress keeps cortisol elevated, leading to anxiety, sleep disruption, weight gain, immune suppression, and cognitive impairment. Adaptogens like ashwagandha have been shown to reduce cortisol levels by 23-30% in clinical trials by modulating the signaling pathways that trigger cortisol release. Rather than suppressing cortisol entirely (which would be dangerous), adaptogens help normalize the stress response — preventing excessive cortisol elevation while maintaining the healthy acute stress response needed for alertness and performance.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How long do adaptogens take to work?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most adaptogens require 2-6 weeks of consistent daily use before significant effects are noticeable. Ashwagandha (KSM-66) clinical trials typically measure outcomes at 8 weeks, though some participants report reduced anxiety within 2 weeks. Rhodiola rosea may act more quickly — some studies show effects within 3-7 days for acute stress and fatigue. The key is consistent daily supplementation, as adaptogens work through cumulative modulation of the HPA axis and stress response pathways. Unlike anxiolytic drugs that provide immediate but temporary effects, adaptogens gradually retrain the body\'s stress response system for lasting resilience.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I take multiple adaptogens together?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes — multi-adaptogen formulas are common and may provide broader stress support than single adaptogens. Different adaptogens work through different mechanisms: ashwagandha primarily modulates cortisol and GABA pathways, rhodiola activates AMPK and serotonin pathways, holy basil has anti-inflammatory COX-2 inhibition, and reishi modulates immune function and calms the nervous system. Combining complementary adaptogens can address multiple aspects of the stress response simultaneously. However, start with a single adaptogen first to assess individual tolerance, then add others gradually. Multi-adaptogen blends should use clinically studied doses of each ingredient, not underdosed proprietary blends.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Are adaptogens safe to take daily?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most adaptogens have excellent safety profiles when taken at recommended doses. Ashwagandha (KSM-66) has been studied at 600mg daily for up to 12 weeks with no serious adverse effects. Rhodiola rosea has been used at 200-600mg daily for up to 12 weeks safely. Some practitioners recommend cycling adaptogens (6-8 weeks on, 1-2 weeks off) to prevent potential tolerance, though this is based on traditional practice rather than clinical evidence. People taking medications for thyroid conditions, diabetes, blood pressure, or autoimmune disorders should consult their physician, as some adaptogens can interact with these medications.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Which adaptogen is best for anxiety?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Ashwagandha (specifically KSM-66 or Sensoril standardized extracts) has the strongest clinical evidence for anxiety reduction. A 2019 systematic review in the Journal of Alternative and Complementary Medicine analyzing 5 RCTs found that ashwagandha significantly reduced anxiety scores on validated scales (HAM-A, DASS-21) compared to placebo, with cortisol reductions of 23-30%. For anxiety specifically, ashwagandha is the first-choice adaptogen. Rhodiola rosea is better suited for fatigue-related stress and mental performance, while holy basil (tulsi) has emerging evidence for generalized stress and mild anxiety.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can adaptogens replace anti-anxiety medication?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'No. Adaptogens are supplements, not medications, and should never be used as a replacement for prescribed anti-anxiety drugs (benzodiazepines, SSRIs, SNRIs) without physician guidance. While adaptogens like ashwagandha have shown significant anxiolytic effects in clinical trials, they work through different and generally milder mechanisms than pharmaceutical anxiolytics. Abruptly stopping prescribed medications to substitute adaptogens can be dangerous and may cause withdrawal symptoms. Adaptogens may be appropriate as complementary support alongside conventional treatment, or for subclinical stress and anxiety that does not meet the threshold for pharmaceutical intervention. Always discuss with your psychiatrist or physician.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do adaptogens interact with medications?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Some adaptogens can interact with medications. Ashwagandha may enhance the effects of thyroid medications (it can increase T4 levels), lower blood sugar (interacting with diabetes medications), and potentiate sedative medications. Rhodiola may interact with antidepressants (particularly MAOIs) and blood pressure medications. Holy basil may lower blood sugar and interact with anticoagulants. Eleuthero may interact with blood pressure and diabetes medications. If you take any prescription medications, consult your physician or pharmacist before starting adaptogen supplements. This is particularly important for thyroid, diabetes, blood pressure, and psychiatric medications.' } },
] };
