    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Adaptogen Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What are adaptogens?</summary><p>Adaptogens are herbs and mushrooms that help the body resist stressors by modulating the HPA axis. They must be non-toxic, broadly stress-protective, and have a normalizing effect on physiology.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How do adaptogens reduce stress?</summary><p>They modulate the HPA axis, reducing excessive cortisol elevation while maintaining healthy acute stress response. Ashwagandha reduces cortisol by 23-30% in clinical trials.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long do adaptogens take to work?</summary><p>Most require 2-6 weeks of daily use. Ashwagandha trials measure at 8 weeks. Rhodiola may act faster (3-7 days). Consistent daily use builds lasting stress resilience.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take multiple adaptogens together?</summary><p>Yes — different adaptogens work through different mechanisms. Start with one, assess tolerance, then add others. Multi-adaptogen blends should use clinical doses of each.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are adaptogens safe to take daily?</summary><p>Most have excellent safety profiles at recommended doses. Some practitioners suggest cycling (6-8 weeks on, 1-2 weeks off). Consult your physician if you take medications.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Which adaptogen is best for anxiety?</summary><p>Ashwagandha (KSM-66 or Sensoril) has the strongest evidence for anxiety. Rhodiola is better for fatigue. Holy basil has emerging evidence for generalized stress.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can adaptogens replace anti-anxiety medication?</summary><p>No. Adaptogens are supplements, not medications. Never stop prescribed medications without physician guidance. Adaptogens may complement conventional treatment.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do adaptogens interact with medications?</summary><p>Yes — ashwagandha may affect thyroid and diabetes medications. Rhodiola may interact with antidepressants. Consult your physician or pharmacist before starting, especially with thyroid, diabetes, blood pressure, or psychiatric medications.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span><p><strong>Important:</strong> Adaptogens are supplements, not treatments for anxiety disorders, depression, or other mental health conditions. If you experience persistent anxiety, panic attacks, or depression, seek professional mental health support. Adaptogens may interact with thyroid, diabetes, blood pressure, and psychiatric medications — consult your physician before starting.</p></div>

